  {
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> Does Ship.js inject an environment variable somewhere? CircleCI (and all CIs) [inject `CI=true`](https://circleci.com/docs/2.0/env-vars/#built-in-environment-variables) to give context to scripts. We could imagine injecting `RELEASE=true`in Ship.js when the job is eligible to releasing (the commit name matches), and throw in the Rollup script if `RELEASE=true` _and_ `VERSION` is `undefined`.\r\n\r\nIt's a good idea to pass an environment variable.\r\n\r\n1. I'd name it `SHIPJS` rather than `RELEASE`, because even if I search for `RELEASE`, I wouldn't be able to find it in our code base which will later confuse us or someone in charge who doesn't know this decision.\r\n\r\n2. Letting Ship.js to inject the env var vs. Updating our package.json to have \r\n```js\r\n\"scripts\": {\r\n  ...\r\n  \"release:prepare\": \"SHIPJS=true shipjs prepare\"\r\n}\r\n```\r\nHmm. After writing this, I guess it'd be better to have it out-of-the-box.\r\n\r\nWhat do you think?",
